<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Bob Andres -- Peninsula Times Tribune; WARMING UP IN GILROY --
Food will be hot -- in many ways -- at the venerable garlic festival.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  FREMONT; WINE; ARTS; FESTIVAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  It may be the Bay Area's biggest festival and fair weekend of the summer.;   
In the center: the Fremont Arts &amp;  Wine Festival. To the south: the Gilroy
Garlic Festival and the first weekend of the Santa Clara County Fair.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FREMONT ARTS &amp; WINE FESTIVAL TAKES CENTER
STAGE
180,000 PEOPLE EXPECTED TO VISIT THIS YEAR'S
EVENT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article this page  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Drawing the biggest crowds last year -- 180,000 over two days -- was the
Fremont Arts &amp; Wine Festival. This year, the festival will be even bigger,
with more than 40 food booths, beverages offered by 10 wineries and five
microbreweries, two entertainment stages and up to 600 arts and crafts
booths.;    The festival, co-sponsored by the Fremont Chamber of Commerce and
the Mercury News, runs from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. today and Sunday on Paseo Padre
Parkway between Mowry and Walnut avenues and down Capitol Avenue to State
Street. Admission is free and there's lots of free parking nearby.;    The
venerable Garlic Festival, which drew more than 142,000 people last year, will
be held today and Sunday from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. There'll be bands, arts and
crafts, a children's play area and lots of food. Mostly made with garlic, of
course. Tickets are $8 for adults and $2 for children and senior citizens.;   
Expect lots of traffic if you drive, taking Highway 101 south to Gilroy and
following the signs.;    And the Santa Clara County Fair is in its first
weekend today and Sunday with the gates opening at 11 a.m. Admission is $6.50
for adults and $4 for children and senior citizens. The fairgrounds abut Tully
Road in South San Jose, which can be reached on Highway 101.;    Today,
highlights include livestock judging, the fair parade and a nighttime
appearance by the Marshall Tucker Band.;    A fair schedule will appear daily
in the Mercury News. Today's can be found in the Living section.  </TEXT>
